Eric Christopher | Crain's


















 




 




 





If I Knew Then...


            In this ongoing series, we ask executives, entrepreneurs and business leaders about mistakes that
            have shaped their business philosophy.
          

            Eric Christopher          



                CEO, Zylo Inc.              






              By Chris O'Malley














Small BusinessStartupsTech 


 


            Background:  
          
Indianapolis-based Zylo Inc. helps organizations manage and optimize their software-as-a-service subscriptions.

The Mistake: 
It was something I was pushing for throughout my career that I’m kind of glad didn’t happen.
When I came out of college I joined ExactTarget, now Salesforce.com. I was one of the younger sales reps on the team. I had some entrepreneurial experience that gave me a way to get in the door.
I had some initial success as a rep. Part of it was because we had this great product and they trained me well.
In the early days, I was always someone who wanted to move up, career-wise. Quickly. I was in my early 20s. I did inside sales. I moved quickly up to outside sales. And I started envisioning myself becoming a manager and moving up really quickly.
I went through year after year. I was an individual contributor for eight years. And I was always expressing at the end of every sales year that I wanted to jump into a management opportunity.
I wanted to take on a different role. Maybe move over to account management or something different. Some of my mentors at the time kind of were coaching me. My long-term vision was to become CEO of a company.
I started envisioning myself becoming a manager and moving up really quickly.

The Lesson: 
Scott Dorsey, who was CEO of ExactTarget, told me one good attribute of a CEO was to be really, really good at sales.
Now being a manager, I’ve coached people similarly, as well. Learning a specific skill set, and doing it long enough, can exponentially enable you to do other things faster.
I spent eight years as a sales producer. I had a lot of experience in sales – much longer than I thought I would. I think that prepared me better to be a VP of sales and actually skip the traditional “move up the ranks” path because, in the startup world, I don’t know it actually works that way.
I think after eight years I was actually in a better place to have learned enough and had enough experiences that I could be a better VP of sales to grow a team and hire really good reps. That’s because I knew what it was like first-hand.
I would sit in meetings and say, “It feels almost like my gut is telling me this or that” to make certain decisions. Someone told me your gut instinct is actually a collection of experiences that you’ve had. So your gut generally is factual, data-driven. That’s what your gut is, it’s really your experiences.
So I think if I had done a year of account management, a year of sales and a year of management – I don’t know if that would have been a better path for me.
I was thinking through how many times I was told “no” in my career to something I wanted early. I’m not saying you should not want to move up, but just appreciate and really try to master a role. Because if you do that I think it creates a lot of bigger open doors later.
Today, you never really get a chance to master a skill.
Follow Eric Christopher on Twitter at @echristopher and Zylo at @getzylo.







